<H3> <TI>   Colombia To Sell 20,000 Barrels of Crude Oil Daily </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2502200594 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1800 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2502200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombian Mines and Energy Minister Guido Nule has 
reported that Colombia will sell between 15,000 and 20,000 
barrels of crude oil daily to Cuba beginning next June. The oil 
will be sold at the normal international price and there will be 
no compensation or barter mechanism, the report adds. 
  Another report from Bogota adds that the Barranquilla 
Municipal Council has condemned the U.S. blockade against Cuba, 
and that Barranquilla and Matanzas will soon be declared sister 
cities for possible cooperation. Cuban Ambassador to Colombia 
Jesus Martinez also paid a visit to Barranquilla. He learned 
details about the project to declare Barranquilla and Matanzas 
sister cities and that this will probably take place when 
Barranquilla Mayor (Bernardo Hoyos) visits Cuba by mid-March. 
The ambassador held a lengthy conversation with the Barranquilla 
mayor. 
  Ambassador Martinez also held meetings with the governor of 
Atlantico Department, (Gustavo Bell), businessmen, health 
officials, university students, and professors. During the 
meetings they discussed prospects for cooperation in different 
fields, many of which will be included in the declaration of 
sister cities. These cooperation prospects will be developed 
mainly in sports and cultural, touristic, and scientific 
activities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

