<DATE1>  28 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2402202194 </F>
<F P=103> PA2402202194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Mexican elections, 
scheduled for 21 August 1994. 
  Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon, campaign manager for 
presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio, of the 
Institutional Revolutionary Party, PRI, is quoted in the "Mexico 
and NAFTA Report" published by the LATIN AMERICAN NEWSLETTERS in 
London. Zedillo said that for the first time, the PRI will be 
facing a true challenge in the elections. "We will have to 
attain full credibility," he said adding that the party "will be 
judged much harder than other political parties." (Madrid EFE in 
Spanish 1610 GMT 17 Feb 94) 
  Colosio on 17 February visited Chilpancingo, Guerrero State, 
where he met with PRI members. Colosio told them that his main 
commitment is "to struggle decisively against inequality." 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 
94) 
  Colosio on 18 February met with small scale entrepreneurs of 
Mexico City and offered them a nine-point plan that will promote 
associations, training programs, loan programs, and tax 
programs. (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 
GMT 19 Feb 94) 
  National Action Party, PAN, presidential candidate Diego 
Fernandez visited Toluca and met with Mexico State businessmen. 
Fernandez told them that "with or without changes to the 
Electoral Law, the 21 August elections will be clean elections." 
He added that he is opposed to the "coalitions that parties 
such as the Party of the Democratic Revolution, PRD, are trying 
to make." (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 
GMT 18 Feb 94) 
  Fernandez also visited Veracruz and clarified that the 
government must comply with the law, but candidates and the 
political parties must also be serious and honest if Mexico is 
to have clean elections. (Mexico City XEW Television Network in 
Spanish 0435 GMT 19 Feb 94) 
  PRD presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas visited 
Durango State where he held a news conference with the local 
media to reiterate his request "for an extraordinary meeting of 
the Congress of the Union to make changes to the Electoral Law." 
Cardenas also said that he would like to meet with PRI 
presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio and "define the 
necessary measures for changes to the Electoral Law and to 
discuss the Chiapas armed conflict." (Mexico City XEW Television 
Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 94) 
  Cardenas also attended a rally in the Durango main plaza and 
spoke of the struggle "to seek a democratic change in the 
nation." As part of his program, he proposed the "economic 
recovery of the country." (Mexico City XEW Television Network in 
Spanish 0435 GMT 19 Feb 94) 
  Rafael Aguilar, presidential candidate for the Cardenist 
Front for National Reconstruction Party, PFCRN, visited Tlaxcala 
State on 17 February. Aguilar said that his party is undergoing 
"a process of tripling its forces, and this proves that by April 
it will have reached its goal of signing up 1 million members." 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 
94) 
  In Veracruz, Aguilar pointed out that the elections are the 
only path for obtaining the democratic change all Mexicans need. 
In a news conference, the PFCRN candidate stated all 
presidential candidates seek honest and clean elections. (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 19 Feb 94) 
  Alvaro Perez Trevino, presidential candidate of the 
Authentic 
Party of the Mexican Revolution, PARM, met with party members in 
Naucalpan. Perez said that "to combat voting abstentions, it is 
necessary to encourage women and youths to vote since they 
represent 70 percent of the country's population." (Mexico City 
XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 94) 
  Pablo Emilio Madero, National Opposition Union, UNO, 
presidential candidate, visited Michoacan State where he met 
with reporters. Madero stressed the importance of clean 
elections that "will serve as an example for future elections." 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 
94) 
  Mexican Green Ecologist Party presidential candidate Jorge 
Gonzalez Torres has visited Michoacan State where he met with 
professors who are on strike at the local university. (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 18 Feb 94) 
  While in Mexico City, Gonzalez Torres accepted an invitation 
to attend the Chiapas peace dialogue as an observer at the 
invitation of the peace commission and the mediator. (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 19 Feb 94) 
  The weekly magazine ESTE PAIS on 18 February reported on a 
poll conducted in Mexico City, Monterrey, Guadalajara, Tijuana, 
and Merida on 11 February. The poll showed that 35 percent of 
the people do not know for whom they are going to vote, 33 
percent said they will vote for Colosio, 17 percent will vote 
for Fernandez, and 14 percent will vote for Cardenas. 
Meanwhile, 40 percent of those polled said they do not believe 
their votes will be respected. (Mexico City Radio ACIR Network 
in Spanish 0030 GMT 19 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

