<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unity Movement Candidate Criticizes Onusal's Assessment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2702161494 San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network in 
Spanish 1800 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2702161494 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Imelda Alvarenga; from the "Facing the Moment" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Jorge Martinez, Unity Movement presidential 
candidate, expressed disagreement on Wednesday with the Onusal 
[UN Observer Mission in El Salvador] Electoral Division's 
assessment that the Supreme Electoral Tribunal [TSE] registry is 
satisfactory. The Electoral Division's second report terms as 
satisfactory the voter registry even though approximately 60,000 
persons will not be able to vote for lack of a voter 
identification card. 
  [Begin Martinez recording] We consider the TSE's response to 
be insufficient. Too many people have been left without their 
voter identification cards. Tens of thousands of people who are 
registered to vote have been denied the right to be told why 
they will not get their voter identification cards. They are 
simply not given one. It is also said a large number of citizens 
requested their voter identification cards but their data was 
lost in the computers' memories. We believe things could have 
been improved. [end recording] 
  Furthermore, the Unity Movement candidate criticized ARENA 
[Nationalist Republican Alliance] for using state resources in 
its campaign. [Begin Martinez recording] The media has been 
invaded by the government with a shameless electoral publicity 
in favor of ARENA. In fact, state-owned presses, like the one at 
the National Geographic Institute, have been printing political 
propaganda for ARENA. This has been reported by the workers. 
[end recording] 
  Finally, Jorge Martinez announced that municipal government 
plans are being discussed with different candidates throughout 
the country. Martinez said his party's main strategy will be to 
sponsor the citizens' participation through open town council 
meetings. 

</TEXT>

