<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Promotes Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2802044894 Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2802044894 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maria Elsa Suarez; from the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] After a meeting with President Violeta Chamorro, 
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgiy Mamedov said Nicaragua 
and Russia will strengthen trade relations. The deputy foreign 
ministers of both nations signed a cooperation agreement, and 
the Russian official met with Presidency Minister Antonio Lacayo 
later in the afternoon. 
  Mamedov told President Violeta Chamorro of his government's 
desire to strengthen bilateral relations by creating mixed 
enterprises, supporting the geothermal industry, and providing 
technical assistance. He also expressed President Yeltsin's 
desire to meet with President Chamorro in the near future. 
  [Begin Mamedov recording] We told President Chamorro that 
the 
United States could equally contribute to the democratic 
transformation in Nicaragua. I have also told President 
Chamorro that I visited her office five years ago when someone 
else was there, but this time I felt more comfortable. [end 
recording] 
  Mamedov also met with Presidency Minister Lacayo. They 
discussed ways to strengthen bilateral trade and the 
transformation process in both countries. 
  The Nicaraguan and Russian deputy foreign ministers signed a 
protocol on consultations between both foreign ministries. 
  Nicaraguan Deputy Foreign Minister Jose Pallais spoke during 
the ceremony: 
  [Begin Pallais recording] Russia has significantly 
contributed to the achievement of democracy and peace in Central 
America. In the future, we hope to strengthen and increase 
commercial relations between our countries. [end recording] 
  Nicaragua's foreign debt with Russia is approximately $500 
million. The renegotiation of that debt is pending. 
  [Begin Mamedov recording] My personal opinion is that we 
could and should forgive part of the debt. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

