<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thirty Companies Bid for Oil Drilling Contracts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2802040094 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 25 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2802040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Francisco Acosta, energy and mines minister, has 
announced that 30 companies have requested registration 
documents to participate in the seventh round of oil concession 
bidding. Acosta issued a communique stating that so far 24 
companies have purchased documents for the Amazon region, and 
six have purchased packages for the coastal and offshore sites. 
  There are a total of 13 drilling sites on the block, 
including 10 in the Amazon region. The other three are located 
alongside and off the Ecuadoran coastline. The concessions 
include strict environmental conservation requirements. 
National park areas and special reservations have not been 
included. The oil companies that are awarded drilling rights 
are expected to lay 7 km of [word indistinct] and drill 15 
exploratory shafts. The investment is estimated at $150 
million. The bidding will conclude on 31 May with the 
presentation and adjudication of contracts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

