<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamber of Deputies, Senate To Review Banco Latino Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2602165094 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2602165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Marcano from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Chamber of Deputies approved in its first 
debate an emergency bill to solve the Banco Latino crisis, and 
the Executive Branch will possibly promulgate that legal 
instrument next week. The debate began at the lower chamber at 
1630. The legal instrument establishes the necessary norms so 
people who deposited their money in the bank may recover their 
money. 
  [Begin Walter Marquez, Banco Latino Commission chairman, 
recording] The deputies agreed to approve the bill in the first 
debate. The proposed changes in style and content will be 
reviewed during the second debate. The president has announced 
that an urgent meeting will be held on Monday to complete the 
process for the bill's approval. Congress will be in permanent 
session until the bill is fully approved on Monday afternoon or 
evening. The Senate should review it on Tuesday, and the 
documents will be sent to the president on Tuesday or Wednesday 
for promulgation. [end recording] 
  The Chamber of Deputies' Finance Commission has been in 
permanent session since Thursday in order to prepare the 
respective report. 
  [Begin unidentified deputy recording] The bill seeks to 
achieve two goals: first, to regulate this specific emergency at 
Banco Latino and guarantee account holders will be able to 
recover the largest amount of money possible; second, to prevent 
similar situations from occurring in the future. Do you see the 
importance of this text? [end recording] 
  The Chamber of Deputies debates will possibly continue 
during 
the weekend because the Finance Commission, which is in 
permanent session, is expected to present a report on Friday for 
the second debate on Saturday. Hence, the deputies will approve 
the bill, thus allowing the Senate to begin its first discussion 
on Tuesday. The special bill for Banco Latino will probably be 
sanctioned by Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

