<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arias Says Caldera Not Pressing for Accused Officers' 
Discharge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2602033794 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2602033794 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cecilia Pachano from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Lieutenant Colonel Francisco Arias Cardenas said 
today at Miraflores Palace none of the accused in the 4 February 
and 27 November events have been pressured by the executive for 
their discharge. 
  The meeting between Arias and the president lasted more than 
half an hour. In an atmosphere of cordiality, Arias told 
President Caldera of some of his beliefs on what has happened in 
the country. During a lengthy news conference after the meeting, 
Arias told journalists of the president's receptiveness toward 
his proposal. He affirmed his confidence in the president's 
capability to lead the country. The military officer ruled out 
any possibility of a coup in the new political scenario in 
Venezuela. 
  [Begin Arias recording] All the proposals I made to the 
president were received honestly and sincerely, very openly and 
frankly. I informed him of the large number of officers who 
want only to return to the Armed Forces. Most of the officers 
who remain in prison have no political designs; they have no 
aspiration to power. They only want to serve their country, and 
they believe they can best do so in the Armed Forces. 
  I also told the president the reconciliation process is not 
the victory of old ways. I told him the vision I, and many 
others, have about this pacification and harmonization process 
is one of a united Armed Forces. The Armed Forces, which for a 
long time have been considered the country's moral reserve, have 
had the capacity for division so as to originate this new 
situation the country is beginning to experience. [sentence as 
heard] [end recording] 
  Arias expressed support for a pacification based on pardons 
and a concerted effort to build a dignified and honest country. 
He said that although for the time being he will not work to 
build his political career, this idea has not been totally ruled 
out. 

</TEXT>

