<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rossi Weapons Firm Sells Shotguns to Thai Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2502144594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 22 Feb 
94 p 29 </F>

<F P=103> PY2502144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Lilian Bem David] </F>
  [Text] Porto Alegre -- The Amadeo Rossi Weapons and 
Ammunition Inc. of Sao Leopoldo, Rio Grande do Sul, closed a 
deal with the Thai Army to supply 6,000 single-barrel shotguns 
for $280,000. This was reported by company exports manager Rubem 
Faggiano. The .12-gauge Pomba-230 shotguns will be inspected on 
21 March by the Royal Thai Army-Bangkok, and will be shipped 
immediately from the Port of Rio Grande. The payment will be 
made in cash through a letter of credit, Faggiano reported. 
  This is the first sale Rossi has made to Thailand after 
winning an international bid last October. Rossi Inc. 
manufactures nearly 20,000 Pomba-230 shotguns per year, 7,000 of 
which are exported to Argentina. "New markets for this kind of 
weapon are opening in Africa and the Middle East," Faggiano 
said. Five hundred shotguns, which will be shipped in April, 
were sold to Papua New Guinea for $30,000, Faggiano said. 
  Long-barrel weapons are responsible for less than 20 percent 
of Rossi's sales. About 3,500 of these weapons are manufactured 
per month. The $30 million sales Rossi made in 1993 were 
principally obtained through the sale of handguns, of which 
Rossi manufactures 20,000 to 22,000 per month. 
  Handgun exports amounted to $18 million last year in 
comparison with $14 million in 1992 and $9 million in 1991. From 
40 to 45 percent of the export production is sold in the U.S. 
market. Last January, the special Rossi 720 .44-caliber with a 
four-inch barrel for five shots, received an award as "the best 
imported handgun" from the American Fire Arms Institute 
[preceding four words in English] made up of U.S. weapons 
manufacturers. 
  This year, Rossi will launch a .22-caliber Magnum revolver 
and the entire .357-caliber Magnum line with ventilated ribs and 
stainless steel parts. Rossi also will launch the six-bullet 
Snubby revolver, a .38-caliber special (SPL) small gun that 
weighs nearly 700 grams and which is being manufactured for five 
bullets so far. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9953 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat039_m_94008" </HT>


