<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   New 13 Nov Civic Movement Demands Coupists' Release </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2302131094 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2302131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The brand-new 13 November Civic Movement has 
demanded the release of the Army officers who are serving 
sentences at San Felipe. One year after the military court 
sentenced 25 Army officers to prison for an alleged coup d'etat 
attempt, leaders of the 13 November Civic Movement said this was 
an unconstitutional ruling, therefore it is invalid. 
  General Luis Pastor Vives, president of the organizing 
committee, called for the release of his comrades in arms, 
arguing that the government's uncompromising position had 
priority even though favorable circumstances exist, like the 
promulgation of the new Constitution. A message from Gen. 
Salinas Sedo was transmitted during a news conference in which 
he expressed his disagreement with his sentence although he 
emphasized he preferred prison to an undignified freedom. 
Meanwhile, his attorney indicated that Congress should pass an 
amnesty law for the prisoners. 

</TEXT>

