<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   FARC Rebels Promise Not To Kidnap Mayors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2702135294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2702135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The top leaders of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of 
Colombia [FARC] told TV Today that they will not sabotage the 13 
March elections and that they are drafting a political proposal 
for the country. They also promised not to kidnap any more 
mayors, but they warned that they will continue with their 
military actions until they achieve a peace agreement. Because 
of legal reasons we cannot transmit the voices of those who were 
interviewed, but in the next report we are going to present the 
basic points of their proposals. 
  The FARC members said they will not sabotage the next 
elections and guaranteed that people will be able to vote 
without any problems on 13 March. We absolutely agree the people 
should be allowed to express themselves by voting for the 
candidates they want as their representatives. We are not going 
to sabotage the elections because we believe it is the right of 
all our fellow countrymen, they said. 
  The FARC members note that if some politicians were withheld 
it was only temporarily and only to discuss their positions. We 
may decide to talk to someone as it is the only option we have. 
That is part of the activities conducted by each front, they 
said. 
  The FARC said they would continue to promote a proposal for 
a 
national reconstruction government. To achieve that they will 
continue to carry out propaganda activities and said the 
confrontation situation will continue. As long as there are no 
agreements the guerrillas will continue to operate. We are 
strong and have many possibilities, the FARC leaders said. 
  They say steps have been taken to join the National 
Liberation Army, and they support the peace process between the 
government and the Socialist Renewal Current. They say anything 
done for peace in Colombia is fine with them. 
  As for possible dialogues between the National Guerrilla 
Coordinating Board and the government, they say the time is not 
right and that the solution to the guerrilla problem is linked 
to the solution of the country's big problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

