<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Marcos Says Government Not Responding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0103025694 Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 28 Feb 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> PA0103025694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City UNOMASUNO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Victor Torres, Humberto Rios, and Juan de Dios </F>
Garcia] 
  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas, Chiapas, 28 Feb -- 
Subcommander Marcos has stated the delays at the negotiating 
table are due to the lack of response from the federal 
government to eight points of national interest related to 
democracy, amendments to the electoral law and the Criminal 
Code, aspects of the ownership and use of land, and respect for 
and a new relationship with Indian communities. 
  The EZLN [Zapatist National Liberation Army] representative 
commented that so far there are "just pieces of paper" at the 
negotiating table. For that reason, he expressed his certainty 
that this phase will conclude without specific agreements. 
Those pieces of paper, he affirmed, do not yet give security or 
guarantees to Indians that they will live well or feed 
themselves. 
  He said those points will have a bearing on the future of 
Mexico and noted the EZLN is not prepared to lay down its 
weapons, since it is certain that the pacification process in 
Chiapas is not simple. The signing of a peace accord, he added, 
will not be fast or easy to attain, and many days will pass in 
order to obtain satisfactory responses to the proposals by the 
EZLN General Command. 
  During a private meeting with foreign correspondents, the 
subcommander felt all the demands on the list submitted to 
Manuel Camacho Solis, commissioner for peace and reconciliation 
in Chiapas, can be resolved by the federal authorities with a 
total commitment and interest in improving the conditions in 
which Mexico's Indians live. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

