<H3> <TI>   Foreign Secretary on U.S. Immigration Laws </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2802154294 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2802154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enrique Tellaeche from Tijuana, Baja California; </F>
from the "Good Morning From Mexico" newscast] 
  [Text] Mexican Foreign Secretary Manuel Tello Macias said 
in Tijuana that there is still time for the U.S. Government to 
reconsider some antimigratory measures to be implemented in 1994 
and 1995 within the framework of a plan presented by U.S. 
Attorney General Janet Reno. 
  At the conclusion of a Mexican Foreign Service meeting in 
preparation for the binational meeting with the United States to 
take place on 7 March in Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas, Tello Macias 
said that there is the possibility that some measures announced 
by the neighbor to the north could be set aside. He rejected 
accusations made Saturday by Chicanos, according to whom the 
Foreign Secretariat spends more resources and time on organizing 
the commemoration of holidays than on providing consular 
protection. 
  Tello Macias said that violence against any single Mexican 
citizen will be considered an act of violence against Mexico's 
integrity. The man responsible for the country's foreign policy 
said he does not know of any plans to construct a barbwire fence 
parallel to the metal fence that already exists along the border. 

</TEXT>

