<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Sets Peace Talks To Begin Between 3-7 March </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0103011694 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 26 Feb 
94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> PA0103011694 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The next round of Guatemalan peace talks will take 
place between 3 and 7 March in Mexico City. An AP dispatch 
reported that according to UN officials the main topics to be 
discussed will be human rights and the end of hostilities. A UN 
statement said UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali set the 
dates for the next meeting after consulting with the Guatemalan 
government and the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity 
(URNG) guerrillas. 
  On 14 February, a Guatemalan Government official said the 
negotiations between the government and the leftist guerrillas 
could produce a peace agreement by the end of the year. Three 
years of negotiations for peace in Guatemala have yielded 
limited results so far. Of an 11-point plan prepared in 1991, 
only partial results have been achieved on one subject: the 
country's democratization. The next round of talks will center 
on the human rights issue and the end of hostilities, according 
to the sources. 
  The guerrilla war in Guatemala has already lasted 34 years 
and claimed 130,000 lives. The debate about the creation of a 
commission for investigating violations of human rights has been 
a serious obstacle in previous negotiation efforts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

