<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cardoso Denies URV Will Lead to Price Freeze </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2602120594 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
25 Feb 94 Business and Finance Section p 6 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE </F>



<TEXT>
ONLY 
<F P=103> PY2602120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
 Language: <F P=105>Portuguese and Finance </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Brasilia -- Finance Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso said on 24 February the government will control prices 
that are marked up abusively. Cardoso, noting that the creation 
of the Real Value Unit (URV) will not lead to a price freeze, 
warned that "if prices begin to abusively stray from their 
historic path, we might decide we need to control them." 
  Minister Cardoso said the provisional measure that will 
create the URV will not merely be designed to convert salaries. 
"We are going to make several decisions by respecting contracts 
as much as possible; therefore, no private contracts will be 
broken," he asserted. The minister said the economic team's 
idea is to create some rules to convert some of the workers' 
expenditures, such as rent and school fees, because salaries 
will be converted compulsorily into the new unit. 
  The minister said the longer private prices take to be 
converted into the URV, the better it will be for salary 
earners. "Salaries will be modified automatically according to 
the inflation rate." 
  Action will be taken within 90 days against those 
enterprises 
that mark up prices abusively and will be forced to mark down 
prices to those on a date determined by the government. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

