<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Minister Threatens To Resign Over Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2602121994 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
25 Feb 94 Business and Finance Section p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE </F>



<TEXT>
ONLY 
<F P=103> PY2602121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
 Language: <F P=105>Portuguese and Finance </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Brasilia -- Labor Minister Walter Barelli 
disagrees with the economic plan designed by the team of Finance 
Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso on the grounds that it will 
lead to the deterioration of salaries. If the plan is not 
modified before 28 February, when it will be released, Barelli 
will resign. In an effort to convince Fernando Henrique Cardoso 
that Congress will not approve the plan, Barelli asked for the 
cooperation of PSDB [Brazilian Social Democracy Party] President 
Tasso Jereissati -- because party members are dissatisfied with 
implementation of the URV [Real Value Unit]. A PSDB economist 
said that the plan will cause hyperinflation because it will not 
control prices. 
  Barelli did not resign on 24 February only because -- 
clinging to a statement by President Itamar Franco -- he 
insisted on the modification of the plan by 28 February. During 
a meeting between entrepreneurs and unionists on 24 February, 
Vicente de Paula -- the president of the union of Sao Bernardo 
do Campo metalworkers -- appealed to Franco to prevent the 
deterioration of salaries. 
  The president replied that he should rest assured, 
explaining 
that he ordered Barelli to watch the plan's design. "There will 
be no salary deterioration in my government," Franco said. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

