<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sao Paulo Governor's Presidential Aspirations Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2202140894 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
21 Feb 94 p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2202140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sao Paulo -- Sao Paulo Governor Luiz Antonio 
Fleury will boycott today's meeting of the PMDB [Brazilian 
Democratic Movement Party] state Executive Board, at which 
former Governor Orestes Quercia intends to request the party's 
support for his candidacy for the presidency. Fleury is not a 
member of the Executive Board and therefore his presence at the 
meeting is not mandatory. Executive Board Chairman Roberto 
Rollemberg wanted to take advantage of this meeting to ask 
Quercia and Fleury to make up their minds about their 
candidacies. 
  Fleury's strategy is to stall for time so as to avoid giving 
an answer to Quercia's request to endorse his candidacy. Fleury 
still dreams about the possibility of being chosen by the PMDB 
to run for the presidency. He feels his name could be an 
alternative for the party in light of the rejection of Quercia's 
candidacy by national leaders and [Deputy] Antonio Britto's 
[PMDB-Rio Grande do Sul] refusal to stand as a PMDB candidate. 
[passage omitted] 
  Deputy Luiz Carlos Santos [PMDB-Sao Paulo] -- government 
leader in the Chamber of Deputies and anti-Quercia -- is a 
member of the PMDB state Executive Board, but on 20 February did 
not know whether he would attend the meeting. Santos is 
scheduled to go to Bandeirantes Palace [Sao Paulo Government 
House], but he argues that prior commitments in Brasilia will 
prevent him from participating in both meetings. From the PMDB 
bloc in the Chamber of Deputies, Luiz Carlos Santos, Jorge Tadeu 
Mudalen, Ari Kara, Roberto Rollemberg, Wagner Rossi, Walter 
Nory, and Maurici Mariano are considered faithful to Fleury, 
whereas Alberto Goldman, Marcelo Barbieri, Paulo Novaes, Carlos 
Nelson, and Manoel Moreira are considered pro-Quercia. Quercia 
has a large majority on the executive boards of the interior and 
in nearly 300 municipalities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

