<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cocaine Seizure Reveals New Trafficking Route </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2602173194 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
25 Feb 94 p 6 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2602173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Campo Grande -- The seizure on 23 February of 305 kg 
of highly pure cocaine at a police post on BR-262 highway -- 23 
km from Campo Grande, Mato Grosso do Sul State [MS] -- revealed 
a new drug trafficking route. The drug traffickers now are 
crossing through the town of Tres Lagoas in eastern MS on the 
Sao Paulo State [SP] border. As a result of an investigation of 
fast fortunes, Federal Police discovered a gang of Tres Lagoas 
farmers and businessmen. The head of the gang, Osvaldir Garcia, 
belongs to one the town's established families. 
  Police received information about the drugs but could not 
seize the first cargo of 338 kg, which was delivered a month 
ago. The seized cocaine was bought in Bolivia for $2,000 per 
kilo and hidden in a secret compartment in the chassis of a dump 
truck with license plate FV-4435 from Andradina (SP). The truck, 
which was being towed because its engine was ruined, had been 
assembled in the Bolivian town of Puerto Quijarro, on the MS 
border. 
  Part of the cocaine was being sent to Rio de Janeiro, where 
it would be sold for $7,000 per kilo, and also to Europe, where 
it would be sold for $40,000 per kilo. Police arrested truck 
driver Claudio Goncalves, 39, and tow truck driver Benedito 
Cardoso Filho, and are holding them at the Federal Police 
Superintendency in Campo Grande. Osvaldir Garcia and three 
other drug traffickers escaped, but their preventive arrest 
already has been decreed. 

</TEXT>

