<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Posadas Mate Growers Protest Low Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2802210994 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 28 
Feb 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PY2802210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Posadas (DYN) -- Local farmers, upset by the low 
returns that they receive for their crops and pressure from the 
tax man, staged rowdy protests yesterday. From early morning 
farmers cut national Highway 12 near the town of Capiovy, some 
130 kilometres from Posadas, on the road which links Misiones 
Province with the Brazilian border. The farmers, mostly yerba 
mate growers, are classed by the DGI Tax Bureau as being 
self-employed and are being pressed to pay pension arrears for 
the past 10 years. The poor farmers say that they have been 
severely hurt by the tax demands. The protesters, who had camped 
by the roadside, stooped traffic until a judge ordered the 
Border Guards to remove them. Three people were arrested and 
will be appearing in court on Tuesday. The farmers are 
demanding a fixed rather than market price for their crops. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

