<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Confirms Support for President, Democracy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2802195494 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1556 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2802195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 28 Feb (ACAN-EFE) -- The Guatemalan 
Army has confirmed its support for President Ramiro de Leon 
Carpio and the democratic process and asserts in a communique 
released today that the head of state has preserved the 
"apolitical nature" of the Armed Forces. 
  The Army denied that the president had intended to implicate 
it in political-electoral activities, as General Jose Luis 
Quilo, the dismissed chief of the General Staff of National 
Defense, asserted on Friday. "No effort has been made to 
manipulate the Army, and the president has not handed down 
instructions to influence the Civil Defense Volunteer 
Committees," the communique underscored. 
  Quilo accused de Leon of having asked Army commanders to 
exert pressure on the civilian patrols so they would vote in 
favor of the constitutional reforms during the popular 
referendum on 30 January. 
  The president and Defense Minister General Mario Rene 
Enriquez denied the allegations, and they both pointed out that 
Quilo's remarks reflected his resentment at being dismissed from 
his post. The Army says the general's assertions were distorted 
and today confirmed its "total respect for the country's 
institutionalism and its support for the current government." 
The Armed Forces also urged every sector of the country to 
intensify its efforts in favor of peace and national 
reconciliation. 
  Meanwhile, the defense minister announced that if Quilo 
insists on leveling accusations against the president and Army 
he could be taken to court. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

