<H3> <TI>   Senate Office Dissociates From Delegation to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0103190794 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0103190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the Senate of the Republic, the office led by 
Senator Bernard Sansaricq has dissociated itself from the steps 
taken in Washington by a group of legislators. In a communique, 
Secretary Ebrane Cadet has expressed the Senate's astonishment 
upon reading the letter sent by a group of legislators who went, 
informally, to Washington. 
  Cadet said that he was surprised to see that the legislators 
referred to Senator Firmin Jean-Louis as president of the 
Senate. The letter was also signed by Senator Yvon Gislain, 
calling himself Senate secretary. 
  The office headed by Sansaricq expressed a number of 
reservations regarding this matter, recalling that under a 4 
February resolution the former office, headed by Firmin 
Jean-Louis, was duly dismissed and replaced by the current 
office, headed by Bernard Sansaricq. 

