<F P=100> Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   CARENA Claims Positive Results From Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0103224394 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1700 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0103224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] CARENA, Action Committee for National 
Reconciliation, reminds the Haitian population that its 
activities at the national and international level have achieved 
many results during the past few days. According to CARENA, some 
of the arrangements include the formation of an ad hoc 
government, a government of concord and of national 
reconciliation under Article 111 of the Constitution, in 
compliance with the resolution adopted at the national 
conference on 6-8 February. The parliament is scheduled to 
examine a law related to this resolution as soon as possible; 
all the steps toward that end were laid out by the office of the 
conference. 
  CARENA also advises that it has outlined to international 
institutions the steps by which, on the one hand, the sanctions 
against Haiti scheduled since the beginning of January 1994 can 
be set aside and, on the other hand, the idea of not hastily 
reinforcing those sanctions can be maintained. 
  CARENA asserts that contacts at the highest level have been 
established for the purpose of immediately supplying the local 
fuel market and that a solution is under study. 
  CARENA claims it is working day and night with national and 
international decisionmakers on the Haitian issue and cautions 
that the task of national reconciliation can not be fulfilled in 
an atmosphere of pressure, tension, and sanctions. 

</TEXT>

