<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Perez Novoa Rejects UN Special Rapporteur Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0203163794 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1200 
GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0203163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cuba has rejected the report by a special rapporteur 
on the human rights situation in Cuba, because it responds to 
U.S. pressures rather than to reality. During a news conference, 
Jose Perez Novoa, Cuban ambassador to the Commission on Human 
Rights, describes as unacceptable the discussion of a draft 
anti-Cuban resolution draft sponsored by the U.S. delegation, 
which will be voted on next week. Perez Novoa deplored the U.S. 
Administration's policy of hostility based on the fact that it 
cannot bring itself to accept Cuba's level of development of 
social, economic, and political programs despite that hostility. 
  Cuba has stated and reiterated over the years that it is 
ready to discuss its differences with the United States under 
conditions of sovereign equality and without preconditions. 
Perez Novoa added that the United States avoids and rejects 
normal relations and a discussion of differences. 

</TEXT>

