<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Signs Contract for Bolivian Gas Pipeline </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0203225194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1949 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0203225194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 24 Feb (EFE) -- The president's office has 
reported that Brazilian President Itamar Franco today signed a 
contract to build a domestic branch of the projected gas 
pipeline that will carry Bolivian natural gas to Brazil. 
  The branch will be 360 km long, stretching between Rio de 
Janeiro and Belo Horizonte. The pipeline's construction and the 
supply of steel pipes will cost $44 million. 
  According to the state-owned petroleum enterprise Petrobras 
[Brazilian Petroleum Corporation], the gas pipeline, whose 
construction will take 14 months and will mobilize about 1,000 
technicians and workers, will allow during its initial phase the 
transport of 640,000 cubic meters of natural gas per day, and 
1.7 million cubic meters by the turn of this century. 
  According to the bilateral agreements, as of 1997 Bolivia 
will supply to Brazil about 8 million cubic meters of natural 
gas from Bolivian gas reserves. It is necessary, however, to 
build a 2,333 km pipeline to carry the gas from the Bolivian 
town of Rio Grande to the city of Campinas in Sao Paulo State. 
  Brazil will build a domestic network to distribute the gas 
in 
those states that are interested in purchasing it, such as Rio 
de Janeiro, Minas Gerais, Sao Paulo, and Rio Grande do Sul. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

