<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2202192594 </F>
<F P=103> PA2202192594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombia's economic developments monitored through 1 
March 1994. 
  Revenues from income taxes, the VAT [Value-Added Tax], and 
foreign trade increased by 44 percent in 1993 following the 
implementation of the tax reform law passed in 1992. The 
Treasury collected 400 billion pesos during the first half of 
February and expects to collect 200 million pesos in the third 
week. The treasury placed a sizable portion of the collected 
funds in securities to prevent instability in the financial 
system. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 16 Feb 94) 
  Colombia and Romania have signed a commercial cooperation 
agreement whereby beginning in September Romanian campers will 
be assembled in Colombia. During a recent visit to Colombia, 
Romanian Trade Minister Cristian Ionescu told his Colombian 
counterpart that his government would like to import Colombian 
coal for energy production and coke [coal residue], coffee, and 
bananas in exchange for Romanian-made mining equipment. Ionescu 
also proposed his country as a distributor of Colombian coffee 
and expressed interest in an aerial route between Romania and 
South America. (Paris AFP in Spanish 1811 GMT 22 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

