<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Downplays Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0203214094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0019 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0203214094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 1 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- The Guatemalan 
Government today downplayed the request by the Attorney 
General's Office for the declaration of a state of emergency in 
view of the rumors of an alleged conspiracy to topple the 
government. 
  Hector Luna Troccoli, secretary general of the presidency, 
told the media that the request made by Attorney General 
Telesforo Guerra was "on a personal basis, and as any other 
citizen, he has the right to give his opinion." 
  Luna explained that this extreme measure -- which is part of 
the Public Order Law -- can only be issued personally by the 
president, Ramiro de Leon, or with the consensus of the cabinet 
when the situation merits it. 
  According to the official, that is not the situation in 
Guatemala at this time. Luna Troccoli admitted that these 
"comments have been made in informal talks," but he reiterated 
that De Leon "has not given any consideration to declaring a 
state of emergency because the circumstances do not really call 
for it." 
  The Attorney General's Office charged there is a plan to 
destabilize the government of Ramiro de Leon in which 
politicians, judges, and union leaders are reportedly involved, 
but he abstained from giving their names. Nonetheless, the 
political parties and the union leaders have demanded that 
Guerra present evidence of the alleged plot, which the attorney 
general linked to a strike movement of the public workers who 
are demanding salary increases. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

