<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sergio Ramirez on Social Democracy, FSLN </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20433A </F>
<F P=103> 94P20433A </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua EL NUEVO DIARIO in Spanish of 14 
February 1994 on page 7 reports that Sandinist deputy Sergio 
Ramirez remarked to the head of the German Press Agency for 
Mexico and Central America that the Sandinist National 
Liberation Front (FSLN) "needs to bury its political-military 
past and strive to be a modern party...capable of confronting 
the problems of the great majority." He said that FSLN leaders 
must communicate more with the voters and bear in mind that they 
represent a party "which rejects all methods of violence...." 
Turning to the current crisis, Ramirez said that the 
government's greatest weakness in its economic policy is 
"ignoring the massive problems of the population" and 
"overemphasizing the dictates of the international financial 
organizations." Stating that he is against neoliberal policies, 
Ramirez also said that he has no intention of seeking the 
position of FSLN secretary general. In response to a question 
about the social-democratic nature of the FSLN, Ramirez 
explained that while the FSLN is a member of the Socialist 
International, there is a current within the Front which 
represents "the democratic left." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

