<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   MPD Members Occupy Electoral Tribunal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0303005994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0014 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0303005994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 2 Mar (EFE) -- Approximately 400 activists of 
the leftist Democratic People's Movement (MPD) today occupied 
the headquarters of the Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) in 
defense of a candidacy for the 1 May legislative and municipal 
elections. The peaceful occupation, in which dozens of workers 
and peasants are participating, was undertaken after it was 
rumored that the candidacy of Antonio Ponce, MPD candidate for 
deputy from the northern Andean Province of Imbabura, was going 
to be disqualified. 
  MPD leader John Pule accused the TSE members, who belong to 
populist, Social Democratic, and rightist parties, of trying to 
disqualify that candidacy. Nevertheless, he did not explain the 
reason for that fear. 
  Acting TSE President Medardo Oleas and some TSE members are 
meeting with the leaders of the building's occupiers, which is 
located in a residential area in northern Quito, to try to solve 
the problem. 
  The TSE is finalizing the details of the legislative, 
municipal, and provincial elections that will be held in three 
months. These will include a plebiscite on several 
constitutional reforms announced yesterday by Ecuadoran 
President Sixto Duran-Ballen. 

</TEXT>

