<H3> <TI>   Depositors of 2 Banks Occupy Dutch Consulate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0203230694 Caracas EL NACIONAL in Spanish 2 Mar 94 p E-11 </F>
<F P=103> PA0203230694 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL NACIONAL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Marin] </F>
  [Text] On 1 March, representatives of the so-called 
National Front for the Defense of Banco Latino and Banco 
Hipotecario de Occidente Depositors [Frente Nacional Pro-defensa 
de los Depositantes del Banco Latino y del Banco Hipotecario de 
Occidente] occupied the Dutch Consulate in this city [Maracaibo, 
Zulia State capital]. 
  Elias Mata and Aurelio Mhr said that this measure seeks to 
expose to international public opinion the financial problems 
depositors have had to face since the intervention of Banco 
Latino. In this particular case, they want the Dutch consul to 
ask the Dutch ambassador to Venezuela and Venezuelan Foreign 
Minister Miguel Angel Burelli Rivas to suggest to the Dutch and 
Venezuelan Governments that they establish a commission to 
investigate the Latino NV Curazao case. 
  They also urged the Dutch and Venezuelan Governments "to see 
that the culprits in the Latino NV Curazao case are punished." 
We are also demanding that the Dutch Government guarantee 
deposits that are currently frozen in Latino NV, Curazao. This 
action also demands the expeditious treatment of an emergency 
law submitted for Congress' consideration, they added. Front 
members asked the national government to allow "representatives 
of those affected by the Banco Latino and its branches crisis to 
participate in the commissions discussing the emergency law." 
  This afternoon, Dutch Consul George Vinck reportedly gave 
the 
protesters a document written in English, which reportedly 
states his government's position on this situation. 

</TEXT>

